< text>
I just finished moving out of my apartment at OceanAire after living there for 9 months. I was moving to the Bay Area and needed to find something quick, easy, and safe and OceanAire was just that. I knew I couldn't stay long term due to it being out of my budget but it would be manageable for the short term with money I had saved. If money wasn't an issue I would have never left! They're pricey but it's definitely worth it.

Not only is the quality of living very high but their team of staff is what makes them truly stand out. Gina helped me from the beginning, showing me the units that were available and everything else after with getting approved and signing the lease. She should be the standard for leasing agents, so patient, warm and personable, and not pushy whatsoever.

The manager, Zee is also one of the nicest people I've come across in the CA rental industry. She's incredibly responsive to emails and any issues and is really everything you'd want in an apartment manager.

Maintenance requests were always resolved very quickly which was really nice. I really can't think of 1 bad or negative thing over the last 9 months I spent there. Definitely an amazing place to live if you have the chance, take it!</text>

< Review>
I really enjoyed my stay at OceanAire. The places are very well kept, as are the grounds. All my neighbors were really friendly. I enjoy having the car garage as well. The location is next to Safeway, and a few really good food places. My favorite is Camelot, I really like their chicken strips and fries.

Zee was the person I enjoyed working with most. She is a really genuine, sweet, and helpful person. I always enjoyed visiting with her, and she was very prompt and professional in all my dealings.

I would highly recommend OceanAire! Please tell Zee that Phil says hello if this review prompted you to contact OceanAire. She will be sure to take care of you.

Sincerely,

Phil Campbell</Review>

< Review>
Me and my friends were looking for a new one bedroom apartment close to San Francisco. We explored around 15 apartment complexes in South San Francisco. We set our priority according following criterias - location, price and conditions. Oceanarie Apartments is the one which met our expectations. It's located just by Pacific Ocean and 15 mins away from SF. Townhouses are renovated newly both exterior and interior. Also, we got $2000 off for signing lease agreement as a promotion. Now we are living here for last 6 months, and thinking to resign our lease for another 9 months. Special thanks to Veronica Avelar and Marisol Espino from leasing office. They are helpful. Also, beach access was restored, so now we have a full access to the beach<//Review>

<user>109805023620756977762</user><username>Leslie Campbell< /username><date>1505606636195<//date>< rate>
1<//rate>
< review>
Horrible Construction/Renovtion Disaster!!

I moved in 4 months ago and this has been going on for 3 months. It's 6 days a week of noise and 7 days a week of inconvenience, unsightly equipment, multiple dumpsters, materials, trash, construction vehicles and debris. My parking is in the other half of the complex, across the street, so I've been dealing with the mess since the beginning of the demo in June.

For over a month, the gym was closed, the common "oceanview patio with free wifi" was covered in junk, the common rec room was closed, and even the office was closed. They haven't used their app even once to broadcast messages to tenants. The grounds have been a disaster since mid-June -- as if they're not even going to pretend to keep up appearances.

In July, I stopped going down to look at the ocean, because they were ripping apart the buildings facing the ocean and it was just too depressing to see the mess everywhere. (PS - they said they were going to restore beach access that was washed out earlier in the year, but I'm not holding my breath. Google Maps still shows the path, but it's gone. Also the Oceanaire property map shows an ocean path, which is not there.)

They haven't done anything to contain the  work to a particular section of the property and complete one building before beginning demo on an adjacent building. Instead they work on another building on the opposite end. They are randomly criss-crossing lengthwise across the property (south-north) instead of working east-west). The way they're doing it, it's as if they're purposely trying to MAXIMIZE the  inconvenience of everyone and make it so that nothing looks pretty or peaceful or at all like home.

I was only given 6 days notice on 9/1 to clear my patio before 9/8 and to keep my windows closed for 2 months for renovation to my building. I had purchased $300 of patio furniture and plants when I moved here, not knowing that they were planning a major renovation and everything would all have to be stored inside.  4 days into my apartment renovation, the wrecking crew cut an electrical line to my kitchen and my refrigerator was without power for about 30 hours (and I'll have to toss everything). In the response to my online Maintenance request early that evening 9/12, a technician showed up at my door at 11:45 pm(!) and left at 12:45 am(!) without any resolution. The 2nd day they brought an extension cord. The 3rd day an electrician came to repair it and left the fridge hooked up to the extension cord and left a mess. The 4th day they came back to plug the fridge in properly and remove the extension cord (because I complained) and they still left the mess on the countertop, plus white handprints on my black fridge and countertop.  My 2nd story balcony was left completely exposed on 1 side for 3 days before they boarded it up. The front porch lights have been ripped off for 3 daya now and it's difficult to watch for hazards at night, especially because they leave junk everywhere in the walkways.

There has been no offer to reduce the rent and I've contacted a lawyer.

The pictures speak 1,000 words!</review>

I have rented in most major cities in California due to my profession, and this is the only place I've ever had issues with like these. This lead to my unit becoming infested with mice in July of 2017. Today, in January of 2018, I still have a mouse infestation. The leasing office is completely incompetent, my agent in particular is unprofessional, lacks overall knowledge, is unreliable and uncommunicative, and often doesn't even return calls, emails, or follow up. Working with her has given me so much stress and anxiety because I cannot rely on her to do her job. < Text>
I have lived at Oceanaire apartment homes for over a year now. The view is great, but don't expect to be able to reach management via the phone or for them to be of any help, or honest.

Normally if you call the leasing office it routes you to a 3rd party company to someone who is in another state...not super helpful if your kitchen is flooding for the third time in a year and you have to shuffle pots and pans full of dirty water every 10 mins or couple of hours for days while not being able to use your kitchen sink or dishwasher. During the pandemic since you cannot walk into the leasing office you can actually get them on he phone, I wouldn't expect that to continue once things resume to normal and they can cut costs.

Maintenance told me the cause of the flooding was the kitchen faucet being installed incorrectly (explains why the kitchen sink turned cold when the faucet indicated hot)

You would think thats the worst right?

During the superbowl my car was damaged by a 6 or so foot long and 2 foot wide piece of roofing tile that came loose that they have failed to repair to this day, 4 months+ after it happened, while my car was parked in between my building and the neighboring one in one of the 3 parking spaces available (if you move here realize it's one assigned parking space per unit and that you will not be able to find a spot on the street past 11PM due to all the homeless living in campers).

Despite the employees expressing sympathy for their property causing damage and significant depreciation to the value of my vehicle, and initialize accepting responsibility, their manager has refused to share their insurance company's information with me so that I can have them cover the $500 deductible.

The garage doors here constantly break and are left open so residents can use their vehicles, so if you own motorcycles don't think they will be safe here, or expect your vehicles to be secure. A few months ago my neighbor had their car window smashed our and their car looted in the garage, fyi.

Oceanaire apparently has valet trash service, I see it itemized on my bill every month, funny my "valet trashcan" disappeared two months ago.

When I initially was checking out Oceanaire the unit I rented was unavailable, so I had to tour a neighboring one.

When I inquired as to whether or not the advertised fireplace worked, I was told "kind of". What they meant was that the fireplace is sealed, but they were kind enough to install a cheap set of fake logs that have lights built into them, look fake and make a loud buzzing noise when turned on, not exactly great for watching TV in your living room or setting the mood for a date.

The hot tub is constantly broken. Prior to the pandemic I think I had access to it about 40% of the time I lived here. When I first moved in the jets in the hot tub were broken....I complained and they pretended it never had jets, even though it had a button to turn them on and and they would weakly run....several months later we got an email exclaiming they had "upgraded the hot tub to include jets". Ah yes, they must have bought the base model. These people treat you as if you just fell off the back of the turnip truck.< /Text>

<Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOUnBM42_UlCZMKLCXFAkjQ7K0LRImd-iFyuLTa=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pictures><Gmap_id>0x808f7b754356e2c1:0xfb38a4865087515a< /Gmap_id><Text>I've been at OceanAire longer than most; four years in November. Over the years the community has had its ups & downs - most noticeably when it underwent major construction for about a year (which drove many of the negative reviews online). They've made some great positive changes since then, most notably in management of the community. This remains a really nice place to live - quiet, comfortable, and with an ideal location right on the ocean. The staff are terrific. They are highly responsive and the maintenance team is the best (particular shoutouts to Mike, Zee, and Omar).
With that said, lately I've been disappointed with the amenities that OceanAire promotes front & center on their website as a value-add to residents. That lovely spa that you see on the home page? Hasn't worked for months; basically all summer. The fitness center? Machines are frequently broken or not properly maintained, and bizarrely there is a personal trainer running her business out of it all day which monopolizes the equipment. Be careful investing too much value in the beach access, because this part of the coastline experiences major erosion, which means restoration efforts need to happen which block or disrupt that access. (The access was closed for over a year when a sinkhole took out a chunk of the path, and as of the time of writing this review the beach is a major construction site due to a necessary rebuild of the seawall.)
Overall, I still recommend OceanAire to prospective tenants, but please make your decision based solely on the apartment itself, and not in the peripheral amenities which have become unreliable and consequently far less valuable.< /Text>< Time>

Thanks Crew!

<UserId.>105329235818721087420<//UserId.><user_name>Sam Robertson< /user_name>< date>
1569618429388</date>
< Rating>
3< /Rating>
< review>
I've been at OceanAire longer than most; four years in November. Over the years the community has had its ups & downs - most noticeably when it underwent major construction for about a year (which drove many of the negative reviews online). They've made some great positive changes since then, most notably in management of the community. This remains a really nice place to live - quiet, comfortable, and with an ideal location right on the ocean. The staff are terrific. They are highly responsive and the maintenance team is the best (particular shoutouts to Mike, Zee, and Omar).
With that said, lately I've been disappointed with the amenities that OceanAire promotes front & center on their website as a value-add to residents. That lovely spa that you see on the home page? Hasn't worked for months; basically all summer. The fitness center? Machines are frequently broken or not properly maintained, and bizarrely there is a personal trainer running her business out of it all day which monopolizes the equipment. Be careful investing too much value in the beach access, because this part of the coastline experiences major erosion, which means restoration efforts need to happen which block or disrupt that access. (The access was closed for over a year when a sinkhole took out a chunk of the path, and as of the time of writing this review the beach is a major construction site due to a necessary rebuild of the seawall.)
Overall, I still recommend OceanAire to prospective tenants, but please make your decision based solely on the apartment itself, and not in the peripheral amenities which have become unreliable and consequently far less valuable.<//review>

< username>
Jessica Ho< /username>
<Text>I've lived here for 2+ years and used to sing praises of the place. I was told that the same management company was kept on after the property was sold and renamed from LandsEnd to OceanAire. However, with all that's going on it's surprising how poorly everything is being handled. As a side note, the beach access - one of the reasons we chose to live here has not been fixed for almost a year now.

CONSTRUCTION: So far, it's been a very poor experience. There's dust, noise, and construction items everywhere. We were given 3 days notice to move all of our patio furniture off during construction with no place to put it all. We were told that, for our specific building, it would be worked on for 2 months and to "keep your curtains drawn to ensure privacy.  Crews will be working at the windows and on balconies with visual access to your home." It's odd that they wouldn't finish 1 building at a time. Much of the parking (including street parking) has been taken over by construction vehicles and building materials. Multiple times, they've also had people enter our apartment for cabling related to the construction. We are given notice, but in reality, what choice do we have if we are not home and prefer that people do not enter? Today is supposed to be the final day of construction; however, the painting is still in progress. It's not going to complete within the deadline they've informed us of.

OFFICE MANAGEMENT: They will make no reasonable accommodations for any of the inconveniences, have no power to do so, and will not point you to people that can help. Our rent continues to increase. Our keys do not work for community shared spaces, and we were told by other apartment renters that we have to get our keys reprogrammed. There's a couple of stoic and rude office staff (with an exception or 2). You eventually give up since it's uncomfortable to list concerns to people that don't care and cannot help.

We still currently live in the complex due to the community of friends that have moved here with us. All 8 of which, not surprisingly, have had their own unhappy apartment issues. My hope is that the management company or owners really take into account what our community members are saying and make an effort to reasonably accommodate for issues. Currently, it just feels like existing apartment renters are being punished for staying here, try to voice concerns, but are faced with stoicism and an "unfortunately, it is what it is" attitude.< /Text>< gmap_id>

< time>
1600561013504<//time>
< Rate>
5< /Rate>
< Text>
Though I haven't been able to frequent T.O.T as much as I would like, it's always a treat at this small restaurant when I can visit. My main meal is the delicious Sukiyaki Donburi. Just sweet and savory enough. But what cemented my love of this place even more is that one evening, pre quarantine, a small older Asian woman who was unhoused came to the front inside the restaurant. Immediately, a security officer came in to physically remove her, and as I was starting to object and inform them that I was getting her food, the server came out with a bag of food for her and let the officer know she was okay to be there.  Upon getting her meal she simply left. I could tell this older lady came from time to time as the servers had already started making something. So this place is just a lovely one, great cozy Atmosphere for dates or friendly gatherings. They seem to help their community and I miss being close enough through work to go often.</Text>

<time>1606929896501<//time><Rate>3<//Rate>< Review>
This place is great and I don't understand why the rating's so low. Bowls are around $16 (plus tax and tip), they don't have an obscenely long line like their neighbor Marafuku does, they bring the food out quickly, the broth is so good, and their noodles are super yummy. Portions are generous too.< /Review>

< Review>
Randomly chose this spot for a late Sunday lunch. Was not disappointed at all. Greeted promptly at the door. Clean  with local art for sale on the walls. I love a place that supports local artists. The Menu had plenty of choices with photos. It all looked wonderful. My friend and I decided to share the seaweed salad, Gyoza, cream cheese wontons, miso soup, and Salmon with mixed tempura entree.  Definitely enough for two. It was all delicious. The miso broth had such good flavor. The tempura was delicately crispy, nice. The Salmon was on point. The gyoza and wontons did not disappoint. Well worth a visit and I will return. Thank you TOT.<//Review>

<text>We came it right before the lunch rush and was seated in a nice booth by the kitchen.  I had not eaten yet so I was very ready for food.

Skimmed the menu and everything looked appetizing.  Lunch Bento caught my eye since I really couldn't make up my mind, was too hungry to think.  The salmon teriyaki gozen, includes appetizer, rice (choice of white or brown - I chose brown), miso soup, and salad.  Appetizers vary.  Today's appetizers included:  fresh tofu topped with green veggie and miso sauce, veggie tempura with grated daikon, few slices of sashimi on a bed of daikon and fresh pickled ginger (YUM!), and zaru soba (just the right amount to enjoy without getting full).  WOW what a bento box!  Price $16.50.  Very reasonable for the feast that was presented.

The salmon teriyaki was grilled to perfection.  And tasted really good with a mouthful of brown rice.  Tempura was crunchy good.  Sashimi was fresh.

Husband ordered the sashi gozen.  And he really enjoyed it!

We both had Sapporo draft.  Washed all the food down well.

Service was good.  And we were lucky to have gotten there just before the rush so lunch was served very timely.

Itadakimasu!</text>< pictures>

< text>
Top 3 ramen I've ever tried. This is a little hidden ramen gem. Walking into this place I wasn't expecting much but after ordering food we were blown away. I've never tried the Nagoya-style ramen but it was super delicious, the broth seems to be tomato based, the noodle perfect, loaded with meat, and fresh leeks and herbs to top it off. It all combined for the perfect bowl of ramen. The sushi here was great too. A huge plus is that while all the other popular sports were packed with an hour wait to sit down, we walked right into this place, sat down, and had our food withing a half hour. I was really impressed and I believe you will be too< /text>

< Review>
(Translated by Google) For dinner on June 27th (Wednesday), head to T.O.T. in Little Tokyo, Los Angeles.

After eating, I learned the meaning of T.O.T from the receipt, but it seems to be an abbreviation for Teishokuya of Tokyo.

First of all, toast!

Orion (Imported from OKINAWA) $ 8.75
It seems that they are imported all the way from Okinawa.

And here is the order from the menu.

Millefeuille Shiso Cheese Cutlet (Katsu Only) $ 17.50

Since there is beer, you can use the cutlet separately without a rice set.

Mille-feuille pork cutlet pork and shiso are filled with cheese. It is a cheese that spreads like pizza cheese.

You can enjoy the freshly scented sesame seeds if you do it yourself. Please match the sauce there.

The sauce of sesame and mustard goes well with the freshly fried cutlet.

The shop has all kinds of Japanese food, but I chose the Millefeuille pork cutlet at the entrance and it was the correct answer.

Thank you for your feast (^_^)

(Original)

<userid>102958538124656955048< /userid><Name>J W<//Name>< date>
1563394723442< /date>
< rate>
1<//rate>
< Review>
I enjoyed 4-5 years of great animal care from the staff at this clinic. It has been my first choice. Until yesterday.

Having had to make the unhappy choice of having to put down a dear dog due to heart issues, I had called ahead and specifically asked for an appointment to quickly put our small pet out of its suffering. The dog was a 15 lb chihuahua mix. I directly expressed my request for a quick procedure following our arrival several times telling them that we would have spent enough personal time with our pet privately before we arrived. I was given a late appointment so that there wouldn't be any scheduling delays, (I was told), and told that everything would be ready when we arrived.

I've had to put down a number of dear pets down before and it's no fun for anyone involved. But I know about how things should go. The expectation is for a peaceful and uneventful passing. Usually the vet administers a preliminary injection of tranquilizer to relax the animal, then a short time afterward an overdose of a powerful anesthesia that allows the tranquil animal to drift quietly off to a sleep from which they never awake.

In this case, we arrived and were shown into a private room that had been prepared appropriately. But that was where things started to go wrong. Dr Pandi was on duty, and came in with the anesthetic hypodermic in hand after a short wait. I had to ask for the preliminary injection; which was provided after several excuses and an additional delay. The tranquilizer injection was given and we were told that the Dr would be waiting just outside the door for us. After about 4 minutes the dog relaxed, but my wife had to chase down the Dr who was nowhere in sight. She finally came in and shaved a back leg to expose a vein into which she would insert the butterfly needle through which she was to inject the anesthesia. Apparently she missed the vein causing the dog to yip and jerk which pulled out the needle and pulled off the tube from the hypodermic. Then she shaved a front leg, successfully inserted the needle, and while the attendant fought to keep the tube attached administered what she said was enough anesthesia for a 40 lb dog. I expected the dog to drift off, but it kept struggling for breath. after several minutes it even struggled and whimpered. I said, "OH COME ON?! REALLY" The Dr gave some excuses about dogs with heart issues behaving differently. Our dog continued to struggle for breath. Finally she offered to give a third injection, and I answered, "PLEASE DO!"  So she left again, and finally returned with a third hypodermic. Then shaved a third leg and made the final injection, which worked after several minutes.

It would be a tragic mistake to redirect the grief of my loss into anger at the vet who facilitated it. I don't believe I am doing that here. My only reason for making this review is to alert others so that they will not have to go through the additional trauma we did in an already stressful and sad situation.< /Review>

<review>This building is a hidden gem of the East Bay. It is a labyrinth of private nooks perfect for contemplation and remembrance. They welcome visitors both to admire the architecture, designed in part by Julia Morgan, as well as to memorialize their loved ones. Additionally, they host musical performances in conjunction with local arts groups that both feed the local culture and, I think, celebrate the residents.</review><pics>None</pics>< Response>

< review>
My father and grandfather reside here, so I visit very regularly. The building itself is architecturally gorgeous, and it's a good place to walk around inside,  out of the heat/wildfire smoke. There is an ongoing issue with fruit flies which I have spoken to the staff about multiple times.
If they were better about the bugs, I'd give 5 stars without hesitation. Some of the rooms have skylights which can open. Unfortunately the skylights were open even with the severe wildfire smoke (at rating of unhealthy) but we easily avoided those rooms and it was a good place to get some steps inside for free.

Again, love the facility and the staff is kind during tough times, but minus one star for aggravating fruit flies in my Dad's area (Chapel of Light) and due to the fact that they had skylights open during unhealthy times.<//review>

<UserId.>107229597489498415667< /UserId.><name>Annette S< /name>< Date>
1447868018052<//Date>
<rate>5< /rate><Text>What an amazing place!  And the staff rivals the buildings for excellence.

I have been coming to the Chapel of the Chimes since I was just a small child.  It was always our favorite hangout to explore without those pesky adults hanging around - we made the place our playground and knew every nook and cranny (probably to the dismay of some adults who were just trying to have a quiet moment!).  It holds such a special place in my heart, not only from those childhood memories, but from recent experiences as well.

A few months ago, I decided that the time had come to make arrangements for my own "after-life" experience.  My mother, as well as many other relatives, had already been interred at the Chapel.  I was lucky to be directed to Ian Ho, who handled everything with professionalism.  He was also very patient as I went through the process of making various decisions, not the least of which was where my remains would be placed.  In the end, I not only decided that the Fountain of Integrity was the place for me, but also decided to remove my mother's urn from the chapel she was in and place it in the same niche that I will eventually occupy.  We also went through the procedure of having my mother's urn re-engraved so that my father's name and dates are also inscribed there (his ashes were scattered elsewhere, per his wishes).

Ian made everything easy for me and I cannot thank him enough.  When the time came for placement of my mother's/father's urn, both he and Matthew were so thoughtful and helpful.

I look forward to visiting the Chapel of the Chimes many times in the future!</Text>< Pictures>

<rating>2< /rating>< Text>
I've waited a while to write this review. I had a crown put in on one of my molars. The procedure was quick, but pain after it lasted over a month. I had to go to an endodontist for consultation to get a root canal because of that. I came back to get the bite adjusted, and they just adjusted it too much. A year later I have a crown that perforated since the occlusal surface became too thin from adjustment. The crown now needs to be replaced.

It's not just the quality of care that I am unhappy about, but also how they handled the payment. I overpaid during the initial visit, and my insurance covered more resulting in a refund due to me. It took me a month and multiple emails and phone calls to the practice to get the refund even after they received the payment from the insurance and deposited into their bank account (this information was provided by the dental insurance confirming that the check cleared). I kept getting vague answers why my refund was being delayed, but finally got the refund.

An extra star is for dental assistants who truly appeared to want to do the right thing.

Looking back, I should never have selected this dental practice for my care.</Text>

<Text>My first time eating Korean grilled offal. The food was great! Service was middling, but there were only three servers for the whole restaurant. The combo comes with your choice of three organs, as well as stew (choice of kimchi vs doen jang chigae), steamed egg, and corn. The intestines were cut up by the server and allowed to crisp up on the cast iron plate. The intestines were crispy, chewy, fatty, and flavorful. We also ordered naengmyun, which was a great complement to the hot food. I was full for the rest of the day. The one complaint is that they forgot the doen jang chigae we ordered but brought it out at the end. Would definitely try again, but I want to try the LA location and try the pork belly!< /Text><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPPYjssJi7zQsD2aDfX9ZbzU7V_LoNxRu75zgQ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPhwc29gYlW7Fvj5HQwsZaIUOR3wXfs-WlYVS4=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pictures><name>Andrew Kao</name>< gmapID>

This place is known for their good 'intestines' BBQ' and it must say they were pretty good!  They open around 3pm and by the time we got there which was around 4pm we were fortunate to find a open table and soon saw people waiting outside for 20-30 minutes.   This place is relatively small with about 10 tables for 4 people and parking spot is also packed.   We ordered one 'large' order of mixed intestines ( you can pick which kind) and it was decent size for 3 people and cold noodle (nengmyun) to cap it off.  Spicy sauce nengmyun is what you want to order, not the cold soup based.  We also saw many people ordered intestines to go and serve at home as they are half cooked when taken out.<//review>

This place is best for the locals.  Faint at heart, keep an open mind. They specialize in beef intestines, but also have brisket and pork belly. < text>
Korean BBQ restaurant specializing in innards.  It is not an all you can eat restaurant but the portions are good size and prices are typical for this type of restaurant.  We ordered the mix innards plate, which consists of small intestine, large intestine and part of the stomach.  They pre cook the intestines and you finish cooking it on a hot plate at the table.  We also the brisket.  This was precooked and not finished at the table, but would have been better if you could cook it yourself.  The staff was attentive and friendly.<//text>

<review>There right now with a flat. Ended up seeing for myself that the other tires needed to be changed. Ernest was the guy at the front desk who helped me. Very nice guy, and knew his stuff. I wanted to buy 4 new BF Goodrich ($50 rebate) and he got me interested in a Toyo Extensa tire (which I looked up to make sure right in front of him), and it checked out. He also told me I'll get a $60 rebate instead of $50 and I think he hooked me up w a Military discount of a few bucks because I am active duty.

Jimmy is the technician who fixed my tires and he literally stopped what he was doing and immediately went to fixing my van tires.

Everyone here was NORMAL. What I mean is, with what I do for a living in the Military, I am always trying to figure out if people are lying to me, being fake, and getting a quick read of people around me. These guys are normal joes trying to make a living. They are not extra nice or extra weird, just perfectly normal and I LOVE that.

To add to this and their level of care and honesty, they came inside and took me out and showed me that one of the back tires was basically new. He GAVE me an old rim with the good tire and said I should keep that as a spare.

Then, as if that wasn't enough, Ernest showed me the rebate for $60 off, took the time to show me how to do it, and showed me how it works. Then he asked me how many kids I have and said I can also get 4 free tickets to a go-cart track in LA that my kids have wanted to go to for a long time.

At one point he couldn't find the promo at first and said that if it was over he would just take $60 off the tires. Very nice man.

This place makes me feel like Pedro still has hope. This place gives you that 1960's feel that Pedro is supposed to give.

Good job American Tire Depot! I was worried because of places like Johnnies Auto Clinic, but this place is good. I am only speaking for the tires and not any other part of this place because I didn't use those services.

< Review>
You gotta give it to this shopping center--they do an amazing job of programming! In conjunction with Arts Brookfield, they manage to pull in some of LA's most interesting artists.
Every week they have a series of happy hours in the food court and some type of art installation or live music.
Went to see Tuxedo last week and it was hopping. A huge crowd that couldn't help dancing to the cool grooves of Mayer Hawthorne.< /Review>
